data.title: How many cats is too many cats

images.description: What up, everybody! Long time no talk. I've been busy becoming the neighborhood cat lady/man. We don’t discriminate here. If you remember me I had adopted a stray cat or it adopted me. https://imgur.com/gallery/8NsJxbz Now we have addition(s) to the family. Well this all started 3 weeks ago when this lady

Gave birth in my backyard. Literally. She was a neighborhood stray who I had seen around but hadn't seen her in a while, so I thought she had moved on. Well, surprise surprise, she was back and she brought kids with her, and as I would find out the next day, she was seriously injured. 
I put food and water out for her and the next day when I went to check she was there and was limping, had a large mass on one side and had a really big open neck wound.

I managed to get her and the kittens in a carrier and took them to the vet. The vet said that they thought she had both been run over and attacked by a dog. The vet was worried she wouldn't make it past the weekend but said if she did to bring her in the following week. I was sent home with a lot of antibiotics and pain meds.

images.description: La Grange .
I study Dante in my off time. One thing that has really started to strike me is Dante's extremely progressive view on homosexuality. Let's talk.

In the 7th circle of Hell, Dante meets Brunetto Latini, his accomplished mentor in life. Brunetto is one of the sodomites languishing in the punishments of "violence against nature". Sounds rather non-progressive, right? Well, bear with me on this to the end.

The thing you'll notice if you read Inferno is how non-sexualised the punishments of the sodomites actually is. This is ground-breaking as contemporaries of Dante's time very often assumed sexualised torment as punishment for of sins-of-the-flesh. You'll also see this restraint in the circle of Lust, where sinners are simply thrown around in a tempest. 

There's some very violent male-on-male descriptions in the 8th circle of Fraud (after Dante meets Brunetto), displaying that Dante was more than capable of providing a gruesome punishment for the homosexual sinners in his Hell. He chooses not to do this.

When re-encountering Brunetto, Dante's first question to the soul is "What are you doing HERE?". Dante recognises his old mentor as a good man and wonders how someone of such intellect is languishing with the damned. 

What follows on from this is a very pleasant and regular conversation. Dante treats Brunetto with more respect than he shows to any of the other sinners in Hell (barring Virgil). His language is extremely proper and you'd imagine this to have been the same kind of conversation he would have had with Brunetto when at study or when bumping into him on a pleasant day in Florence.

It's striking how regular it is.

data.title: At least I know it's working
data.description:
The first dose only gave me a sore arm the next day, but with the second one, the soreness started after a few hours and quickly spread to my whole body. I had a splitting headache in the night that kept me awake for over three hours. That's mostly gone away now, but my whole body is still sore. Even just sitting in my office chair is uncomfortable.

Still, I'll take this over COVID-19 any day. Get the shot, everyone! But to those fortunate enough to be able to take some time off work: if your arm starts to ache mere hours after the second shot, go right ahead and take the next day off, because you could be in for a ride.
